events.description: Martin Luther marries Katharina von Bora, against the celibacy rule decreed by the Roman Catholic Church for priests and nuns.

events.html: • 1625 – King Charles I of England marries Catholic princess Henrietta Maria of France and Navarre, at Canterbury.[6]

events.description: Rhode Island becomes the first of Britain's North American colonies to ban the importation of slaves.
events.html: • 1774 – Rhode Island becomes the first of Britain's North American colonies to ban the importation of slaves.[8]

events.description: The American League of Colored Laborers, the first African American labor union in the United States, is established in New York City.

events.description: Twentieth opera of Giuseppe Verdi, Les vêpres siciliennes ("The Sicilian Vespers"), is premiered in Paris.

events.description: The USS Jeannette is crushed in an Arctic Ocean ice pack.

events.description: A fire devastates much of Vancouver, British Columbia.
events.html: • 1886 – A fire devastates much of Vancouver, British Columbia.

events.description: Grover Cleveland notices a rough spot in his mouth and on July 1 undergoes secret, successful surgery to remove a large, cancerous portion of his jaw; the operation was not revealed to the public until 1917, nine years after the president's death.

events.description: Émile Levassor wins the world's first real automobile race. Levassor completed the 732-mile course, from Paris to Bordeaux and back, in just under 49 hours, at a then-impressive speed of about fifteen miles per hour (24 km/h).
events.html: • 1895 – Émile Levassor wins the world's first real automobile race. Levassor completed the 732-mile course, from Paris to Bordeaux and back, in just under 49 hours, at a then-impressive speed of about fifteen miles per hour (24 km/h).[12]

events.description: Yukon Territory is formed, with Dawson chosen as its capital.
events.html: • 1898 – Yukon Territory is formed, with Dawson chosen as its capital.
